\begin_layout Standard
Here, the first cosine similarity term measures relevance between the query
 
\begin_inset Formula $Q$
\end_inset

 and possible expansion term 
\begin_inset Formula $t_{k}$
\end_inset

 while the second term penalizes the possible expansion term according to
 it's cosine similarity with any currently selected term in 
\begin_inset Formula $T_{k-1}^{*}$
\end_inset

.
 The parameter 
\begin_inset Formula $\lambda\in[0,1]$
\end_inset

 trades off relevance and diversity and we found 
\begin_inset Formula $\lambda=0.5$
\end_inset

 to generally provide the best results in our experiments on the CLEF-IP
 training dataset collection.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The key insight we want to conclude this section with is simply that MMRQE
 does not select expansion terms independently as in practical usage of
 Rocchio, but rather it selects terms that have uncorrelated usage patterns
 across documents, thus hopefully encouraging diverse term selection that
 covers more documents for a fixed expansion budget 
\begin_inset Formula $k$
\end_inset

 and ideally, higher recall.
\end_layout

